            <div class="detail-panel sumfull active" id="panel-summary" role="tabpanel">
              <h4>Summary of performance for the first quarter</h4>
              <p>Our operating profit was approximately 104 million baht, a 33% decrease compared to the previous quarter and a 77% decrease compared to the previous year. You may recall that last year we had an extraordinary profit in the first quarter, which caused the significant difference, but this year we did not have that kind of profit.</p>
              <p>On a year-on-year basis, revenue decreased by 6% and operating profit decreased by 78% due to extraordinary gains in the first quarter of last year. The profit margin decreased from 9% to 2%, while EBITDA, a measure of cash flow generation, decreased by 35% from approximately 900 million baht to 588 million baht. Net profit was 103 million baht, a decrease of 78%. However, our net cash and short-term investments increased by 14% to 11.63 billion baht.</p>

              <h4>Key factors impacting first-quarter earnings</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>An additional 114.5 million baht was set aside because one of our customers in the United States, a hearing aid company, filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy.</li>
                <li>The PMS, SiC and silicon businesses in China weakened and were impacted by the New Year holiday, resulting in decreased revenue.</li>
                <li>In Ayutthaya, we saw an improvement compared to Q4 last year and returned to operating profitability.</li>
                <li>In Lamphun, EMS demand remained stable and operating profit was flat, excluding the aforementioned provisions.</li>
                <li>In China, our IC business saw operating profit increase both quarter-on-quarter and year-on-year, driven by strong demand for EV modules.</li>
                <li>Our EMS business in China declined, as last year's complex tariff situation led most American customers to relocate production; we moved those operations to other business units within the company.</li>
                <li>In the United States, our RFID business improved but remained unprofitable despite increased revenue, due to a significant decline in profit margins.</li>
                <li>In Cambodia, the relocation of manufacturing away from China brought increased revenue and maintained profitability.</li>
                <li>Fluctuations in the Thai baht produced a loss of approximately 63 million baht in the quarter, relative to the average exchange rate in the second half of last year.</li>
                <li>Cash reserves increased 14% year-on-year, but decreased 2% quarter-on-quarter.</li>
              </ul>

              <h4>Hana Micro Lamphun (EMS business)</h4>
              <p>Revenue remained stable at 2.2 billion baht but decreased 19% year-on-year, related to last year's switch to a consignment model — a decline that is now reversing and will begin to increase during the remainder of the year. The automotive sector weakened due to cost pressures and tariffs, while RF, test and measurement equipment, and computing remained strong. We set aside a special reserve of 114.5 million baht for a client of more than 17 years that entered receivership; however, revenue from this company accounts for less than 1% of the Hana Group, so the event did not significantly impact our business. Our medical business continued to grow strongly, and the pipeline of new projects for Hana Lamphun remains very promising.</p>

              <h4>Micro Packaging (EMS business in China)</h4>
              <p>This business was severely impacted by U.S. tariffs, causing many American customers to relocate production. Revenue decreased 8% quarter-on-quarter and 21% year-on-year. We implemented cost restructuring, including some personnel adjustments, to align costs with lower revenue. Despite the downturn, the EMS business in China is expected to remain profitable.</p>

              <h4>Factory in Ayutthaya (IC business)</h4>
              <p>In Q4 we experienced our lowest capacity utilization on record at approximately 43%, but in Q1 we saw improvement, with revenue increasing 5% both quarter-on-quarter and year-on-year and utilization improving from 43% to approximately 50%. We are seeing cyclical recovery and a return of demand, but face difficulty finding the necessary labour and technicians due to high competition in the Ayutthaya and Bang Pa-in areas. Our existing major customers will drive further recovery and improved utilization.</p>

              <h4>Factory in Jiaxing (IC business)</h4>
              <p>The IC business improved significantly, with sales up 16% quarter-on-quarter and over 100% year-on-year, largely driven by very strong EV module activity. Our standard IC business is improving, but as it is a low-margin industry, we selectively reduced some less profitable clients and cut costs to improve overall profitability. The business has returned to profitability following this restructuring, and we believe Jiaxing will remain strong and profitable in the coming quarters. Workload was high in mid-2025, decreased in Q4, and began to recover in Q1; we are confident it will rise from Q2 onwards.</p>

              <h4>United States (RFID business)</h4>
              <p>Although total revenue increased 30% quarter-on-quarter and 5% year-on-year, we were unable to turn a profit due to the sharp drop in inlay prices. This business is growing very rapidly and has attracted large companies, which has driven down prices. We anticipate needing to double the business this year to return to profitability — challenging, but achievable, as we have received many large new orders and are increasing capacity. We expect to return to profitability in the second half, possibly late Q3 or early Q4. The higher-margin tire-tag business has weakened but shows signs of recovery in the second half.</p>

              <h4>Cambodia</h4>
              <p>Our Cambodian factory has benefited from the relocation of business away from China and is progressing well. The ongoing Thailand–Cambodia conflict creates some inconvenience and increases logistics costs but has not halted the business; customers continue to support and grow with us. Sales increased 40% quarter-on-quarter and almost doubled year-on-year. New medical business will contribute to growth, and we are confident Cambodia will remain profitable throughout the year.</p>

              <h4>Overview of end applications</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Telecommunications:</strong> declined, mainly due to the consignment model, and is expected to recover.</li>
                <li><strong>Industrial:</strong> beginning to recover after the turmoil caused by tariff issues.</li>
                <li><strong>Automotive:</strong> slight decrease.</li>
                <li><strong>RFID:</strong> revenue increased, but profit margins decreased.</li>
                <li><strong>Other:</strong> relatively stable.</li>
              </ul>

              <h4>PMS business in Korea</h4>
              <p>This quarter was another difficult one — up 21% quarter-on-quarter but down 36% year-on-year, with the Chinese market weakened particularly by the Chinese New Year holiday. We continue to invest heavily in marketing in India and Korea and are starting to see positive returns, with revenue growth anticipated in Q2. We will also focus on the AI-driven solid-state transformer business, which we believe has high potential.</p>

              <h4>The transition to solid-state transformers (SSTs)</h4>
              <p>A major challenge in building data centers is the enormous amount of electricity required. To support this demand, power companies are shifting from large, traditional magnetic transformers to solid-state transformers (SSTs), which are lighter and smaller, faster, bi-directional (ideal for renewable energy), more efficient, support smart-grid communication, and manage renewable energy and battery storage more efficiently.</p>

              <h4>The importance of silicon carbide</h4>
              <p>Silicon carbide (SiC) will play a crucial role in solid-state transformers because, compared to silicon, it offers much higher switching speed, greater efficiency, higher voltage tolerance and far better temperature resistance. As data centers consume so much power, this is one of the biggest challenges for the expansion of AI — without sufficient power it cannot function — and SiC is central to managing power consumption more efficiently.</p>

              <h4>PMS's technology roadmap</h4>
              <p>The roadmap shows our existing portfolio (blue) and new developments (red), notably MOSFETs, JFETs and SiC JFETs at very high voltages up to 1,200V, 2,300V and 3,300V, for use in solid-state transformers and applications such as railways and new power requirements. This will be developed by Power Master, expected in Q3 of next year, and should drive business towards the end of next year and into 2028.</p>

              <h4>Liquidity</h4>
              <p>We generated approximately 600 million baht in cash flow, down from 900 million baht. We spent 236 million baht, compared to 210 million baht last year, and this is expected to increase. As mentioned, cash increased 1.4 billion baht, or 14%.</p>

              <h4>Updated information about Phononic</h4>
              <p>Hana is building a fully automated, in-house-designed production line, currently undergoing testing and fine-tuning. The qualification process — internal certification, then the customer (Phononic), then their customers — is expected to complete by the end of June. The Phononic technical team visited Hana last month and were very impressed, and recently signed a second large-scale production agreement that doubles the previous order. The first phase of capacity increase takes place in the second half of this year; the second begins in Q1 next year, given equipment lead times. We are also discussing a next-generation Co-Packaged Optics (CPO) cooling project: as 1.6-terabyte GPUs run very hot and require cooling, Phononic has indicated that a successful TEC for this package would significantly exceed the volumes Hana has already agreed to produce.</p>

              <h4>A new AI-driven project</h4>
              <p>Hana has received a new AI-driven project, separate from Phononic, for an oscilloscope to test 1.6-terabyte optical transceivers. These devices monitor high-speed data transfer rates of 240 gigabits per second in data centers; they are expensive but in high demand, and our customer sells them to users such as Meta, Google, Amazon and Microsoft. The project begins in June, with staff training overseas, equipment arriving in Q3, capacity increasing in late Q3, and mass production hoped for early Q1 next year (or possibly year-end). Capex is relatively small, perhaps under $5 million, but working capital will be much higher. In revenue terms it is extremely significant — equivalent to a top-five customer by next year.</p>

              <h4>Summary of AI-driven activities</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Cooling-equipment business for Phononic.</li>
                <li>The newly acquired high-density PCBA business, commencing in the second half of this year and early next year.</li>
                <li>Solid-state SiC transformer devices, expected in the second half of next year.</li>
              </ul>

              <h4>Summary and future trends</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Lamphun:</strong> many exciting new AI-driven projects, with winning more projects a strong opportunity.</li>
                <li><strong>Jiaxing (EMS):</strong> business affected by tariffs has been resized to ensure profitability.</li>
                <li><strong>Ayutthaya (IC):</strong> growing with improving utilization, though employment challenges remain.</li>
                <li><strong>China (IC):</strong> profitability improved significantly, driven by EV modules and power-management activities.</li>
                <li><strong>Ohio, USA (RFID):</strong> challenged by declining margins, but expected to return to profit by year-end as new orders offset lower margins.</li>
                <li><strong>Cambodia:</strong> stable and profitable.</li>
                <li><strong>PMS:</strong> still expected to report losses this year, but market recovery and new projects should bring improvement in the second half and beyond.</li>
              </ul>

              <h4>Capital expenditure (CAPEX)</h4>
              <p>From a very low 626 million baht last year, we forecast a threefold increase this year, potentially exceeding 2 billion baht, depending on when new machinery arrives. If it arrives before year-end it counts as investment for this year; if not, for the beginning of next year.</p>

              <h4>Question &amp; answer session</h4>
              <p><strong>How would a prolonged war affect the company?</strong><br>A prolonged war leads to higher energy costs and inflation, impacting consumer spending. If oil prices remain high until year-end, there are concerns it could affect demand for certain goods in 2027. However, AI-related businesses will not be affected, as their investments are in infrastructure.</p>
              <p><strong>What are the outlooks and trends for the RFID business?</strong><br>The RFID business is growing rapidly, but large companies entering the market have lowered prices and impacted margins. The solution is to increase volume — the company needs at least 80–100% sales growth this year to return to profitability. We have received orders close to that target and are ordering additional machinery, so we expect to return to profitability by year-end.</p>
              <p><strong>Can the company expand its operations in Cambodia?</strong><br>Yes — production capacity is available; the challenge is finding new business, not expanding floor space. As workload increases, we will move machinery from Lamphun to Cambodia. We will soon begin producing medical products (hearing aids) for our long-standing largest customer, who has shifted from remote controls to the medical business; this will be a growth driver.</p>
              <p><strong>Has the Q1 profit reached its bottom?</strong><br>The company does not provide profit forecasts, so we cannot answer directly. We are not satisfied with Q1 but are confident we can improve as the outlook improves. Despite concerns about the war, we hope it will not affect us this year, and we remain confident the company can continue to grow.</p>
              <p><strong>When do you expect PMS to return to profitability?</strong><br>PMS will continue to incur losses this year, but as business clearly improves we expect losses to decrease. The amount will still be significant, but we believe we will begin to see reduced losses in the second half — though the full year will remain a loss.</p>
              <p><strong>What percentage of revenue will come from Phononic?</strong><br>We cannot disclose exact figures, but this business is very important and Phononic could become one of our top 5–7 customers within the next year — more if new projects are added.</p>
              <p><strong>What is the progress of the joint venture with PTT (FT1)?</strong><br>As PTT is the major shareholder, we must comply with their announcements. The situation is unchanged; we continue to monitor the project, but it is currently temporarily suspended.</p>
              <p><strong>Can I request the presentation file?</strong><br>We do not disclose the presentation file, but the session was recorded and is available on YouTube or the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) website, where you can review the slides.</p>
              <p><strong>What are the trends in the gross margin of the IC business?</strong><br>Gross margin across all businesses is affected by two main factors: capacity utilization and exchange rates. IC utilization was very low in Q4 but began improving in Q1 and should continue through Q2 and Q3, despite recruitment challenges. The weakening Thai baht against the US dollar is beneficial, so positive movements in both factors will support improved gross margins.</p>
              <p><strong>Does the company anticipate a loss this year?</strong><br>While Q1 results weren't great, we did not incur a loss, and the overall situation is improving. In principle, we do not anticipate a loss this year.</p>
              <p><strong>Are you concerned about other customers in financial difficulty?</strong><br>For the customer requiring a bad-debt provision, we were unaware until they stopped paying, which was unexpected. Generally, at this time, we have not found any other customers in a worrying situation.</p>
              <p><strong>What are the risks of doing business with Phononic?</strong><br>Risks always exist. One is that the product might fail qualification, which we consider low; the worst case would be a delay to the start of production, not a standstill. Another uncertainty is the actual size of demand, which Phononic reports as enormous. Considering the growth of companies like Nvidia, AI growth appears truly strong, and we are confident in their business — but no one knows the exact future.</p>
              <p><strong>Besides the three projects presented, are there other AI-related businesses?</strong><br>We do have others, but as they are not yet large enough to significantly impact the company, we have not discussed them. We only highlight AI businesses clearly important to Hana's growth; these others have future potential, and if they grow we will be happy to discuss them.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- TAB 2: transcript — real SET transcript (English), prose format, same bounded box -->
            <div class="detail-panel tscript" id="panel-transcript" role="tabpanel">
              <div class="lead">
                <span class="spk">Richard Han</span>
                <span class="role">Chief Executive Officer, Hana Group</span>
              </div>

              <p>Good morning everyone and welcome to Hana's first quarter overview and update. My name is Richard Han, I'm the CEO of the Hana Group. So let's start off with summarizing our first quarter performance.</p>

              <h4>Q1 performance</h4>
              <p>We registered a normalized profit of about 104 million Baht, which was down 33% on the quarter and 77% on the year. You may remember last year we had an exceptional gain in the first quarter — that's why the big difference, and this year we don't. So, year-on-year, revenues were down 6%, normalized profit down 78%. The margin reduced from 9% to 2%. Our cash generation, EBITDA, reduced 35% from around 900 to 588. Our net cash and short-term investments, however, increased 14% to 11.63 billion Baht.</p>

              <h4>Key factors in the quarter</h4>
              <p>Unfortunately, we had to take an exceptional provision of 114.5 million Baht due to one of our customers in America, a hearing aid company, that has filed for Chapter 7. In our PMS business, SiC and silicon were weak in China, with the impact of the New Year dragging earnings down. In Ayutthaya we saw an improvement over Q4 last year and returned to operational profitability. In Lamphun, EMS demand was stable and operating profits were flat, excluding that provision. In China, our IC business operating profits were up both quarter-on-quarter and on the year on the back of strong EV module demand; our China EMS business dropped as American customers relocated due to the tariff situation. In the US, our RFID business improved but remained in the red as margins dropped. In Cambodia, the beneficiary of the move out of China, revenues increased and profitability was maintained. The movement in the Thai Baht produced approximately a 63 million Baht loss in the quarter.</p>

              <h4>Hana Micro Lamphun (EMS)</h4>
              <p>Revenues were flat at 2.2 billion and down 19% on the year — the year-on-year drop relates to last year's change to a consignment model, which is now reversing. Automotive was weak due to cost pressures and tariffs; our RF, test and measurement and computer businesses were strong. We took the exceptional 114.5 million Baht provision for a customer of over 17 years that went into receivership; their revenue represents less than 1% of the group. Our medical business was strong and the pipeline for Lamphun is very strong.</p>

              <h4>Micro-packaging (China EMS)</h4>
              <p>This business was hit hard by US tariffs as American customers wanted to move out — revenues were down 8% on the quarter and 21% on the year. We restructured the cost base to align with lower revenue, so the China EMS group will remain profitable going forward.</p>

              <h4>Ayutthaya (OSAT)</h4>
              <p>In Q4 we hit an all-time low utilization of around 43%, and we saw an improvement in Q1 — revenues up 5% on the quarter and 5% on the year, with utilization improving from 43% to around 50%. Demand is coming back, although we are struggling to find the labour and technicians we need given strong local competition. Our existing major customers will drive the reversal and improvement in utilization going forward.</p>

              <h4>Jiaxing (IC)</h4>
              <p>A much-improved situation for our IC business — sales up 16% on the quarter and over 100% on the year, mainly driven by EV module activity. Standard IC was improving but margins are tight, so we selectively reduced low-margin customers and cut the cost base. The business is back to profitability after restructuring and should hold up in future quarters.</p>

              <h4>United States (RFID)</h4>
              <p>Despite top-line revenue up 30% on the quarter and 5% on the year, we could not break even because inlay prices dropped aggressively. This business is growing very fast and has attracted large competitors driving prices down. To return to profitability we will have to roughly double the business this year; we have secured substantial new orders and will increase capacity, so we expect to return to profit in the second half — towards the end of Q3 or early Q4. The higher-margin tire-tag business was weak but should recover in H2.</p>

              <h4>Cambodia</h4>
              <p>Cambodia benefited from the movement of business out of China. The Thailand–Cambodia conflict is an inconvenience that increases our logistics costs but does not stop the business; customers continue to increase their business with us. Sales were up 40% on the quarter and nearly double on the year, with new medical business coming through. I'm confident Cambodia will remain profitable throughout the year.</p>

              <h4>Korea &amp; PMS</h4>
              <p>A difficult quarter again — up 21% quarter-on-quarter but down 36% on the year, with China weak around the Chinese New Year. We continue to invest in marketing in India and Korea, which are beginning to pay back, and we expect Q2 revenues to grow. We are focusing on an AI-driven solid-state transformer (SST) opportunity. Data centres use enormous amounts of electricity, and utilities are moving from bulky magnetic transformers to solid-state transformers, which are lighter, faster and bi-directional — ideal for renewable energy. Silicon carbide will play an important role because, versus silicon, it offers higher switching speed, efficiency, voltage and temperature tolerance. The new SiC devices (1,200V, 2,300V and 3,300V MOSFETs and JFETs) will be developed by Power Master and are expected on board by Q3 of next year.</p>

              <h4>Liquidity</h4>
              <p>We generated around 600 million, down from 900 million; capex was 236 versus 210 a year ago and will grow; cash increased 1.4 billion, or 14%.</p>

              <h4>Phononic update</h4>
              <p>Hana is building a fully automated, in-house-designed production line for Phononic's thermoelectric cooling device, currently undergoing tests and fine-tuning. The qualification process — internal, then customer, then the customer's customer — should complete by the end of June. Phononic's technical team visited Hana last month and were very happy with our in-house system, and have signed a second mass-production agreement that effectively doubles the previous order. The first production ramps through H2 this year; the second agreement ramps from Q1 next year, given equipment lead times. We are also discussing the next-generation co-packaged optics (CPO) cooling project, where volumes could be significantly higher.</p>

              <h4>New AI optical-test project</h4>
              <p>Hana has won a new AI-driven project (the customer cannot be named) building an oscilloscope to test 1.6-terabyte transceiver optical performance for data centres. The customer sells these multi-million-dollar machines to users like Meta, Google, Amazon and Microsoft. The project kicks off in June, with equipment arriving in Q3 and mass production around early Q1. It uses standard Hana pick-and-place and reflow equipment — capex under $5 million — but is more working-capital intensive. In revenue terms it is substantial, equivalent to a top-five customer within the next year.</p>

              <h4>2026 outlook &amp; capex</h4>
              <p>In summary, we have three AI-driven activities: the Phononic cooling device; the recently won high-density PCBA business (H2 this year and early next year); and the SiC solid-state transformer devices (H2 next year). OSAT is recovering off a cyclical low, IC profitability is improving on EV-module and power-management demand, Ohio should return to profit by year-end, Cambodia will be stable and profitable, and PMS — though loss-making this year — should improve in H2. From a low of 626 million Baht last year, we project capex roughly three times higher, potentially over 2 billion Baht, depending on equipment delivery timing.</p>

              <div class="qa">
                <div class="qa-label">Questions &amp; Answers</div>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>If the war prolongs, what is the impact?</p>
                <p>The war is increasing energy costs and inflation, which affects consumer discretionary spending. If high oil prices continue to year-end, we could see some reduction in demand for our goods in 2027. I do not think the war will impact our AI business, which is an infrastructure build-out.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>ถ้าสงครามยืดเยื้อก็คงยังจะมีปัญหาด้านพลังงาน แล้วก็เงินเฟ้อแล้วมีปัญหาเรื่องน้ำมันซึ่งจะมีผลกระทบสำหรับบริษัท และคำสั่งซื้อก็อาจจะลดลงในปีหน้า แต่ส่วนของธุรกิจของเราที่เป็น AI ไม่คิดว่าจะได้รับผลกระทบเกี่ยวกับสงคราม</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>What is the view on the RFID business?</p>
                <p>It's growing very fast, which is good, but big competitors have driven prices down, hurting margins. The only way out is to grow — for every low-margin unit we have to make more units. We need to grow at least 80%, maybe 100%, this year; we have orders close to that and are ordering more equipment, so I anticipate a return to profitability towards the end of this year.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>ตอนนี้ตัว product มีปัญหาเพราะว่ามีการแข่งขันเรื่องราคาสูงมาก แต่อย่างไรก็ตามในการที่จะกลับมามีกำไรจะต้องมีออเดอร์มากกว่า เพิ่มขึ้น 80 ถึง 100% ซึ่งตอนนี้เราก็มีคำสั่งซื้อเพิ่มเข้ามาประมาณนั้นแล้ว</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>Can you scale up Cambodia?</p>
                <p>Yes — we have open capacity and sufficient floor space; the challenge is winning more work. As we do, we'll transfer equipment from Lamphun. A medical (hearing-aid) product from our first major customer starts within a month or two and should be a driver.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>คำตอบ มีแนวโน้มในการที่จะเติบโตจากลูกค้าเจ้าใหญ่ที่เคยทำ remote control กับเรา แต่ตอนนี้หันไปโฟกัสเรื่องของ hearing aid เครื่องช่วยฟัง ซึ่งก็จะเริ่มภายในเดือนสองเดือนข้างหน้านี้</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>Is Q1 profit the lowest?</p>
                <p>We don't give specific profit guidance, but we're not happy with Q1 and are confident we can improve as the overall outlook improves. The war is a risk hanging over us, but I hope it won't impact us this year.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>ขออนุญาตไม่ตอบคำถามในรายละเอียดตรงนี้แต่ว่า ยังไงก็ตามเรามีความคาดหวังว่า เราจะมีกำไรที่เพิ่มขึ้นจากธุรกิจที่เรามองเห็น จาก outlook ของเรา</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>When will PMS be profitable?</p>
                <p>PMS will continue to lose money this year, but as the business improves the loss should reduce, and I'm positive we'll see a reduction in losses in H2 — though still a loss for the full year.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>ในส่วนของ PMS คาดว่าจะกำไรเมื่อไหร่ PMS มีแนวโน้มในการพัฒนาเพิ่มขึ้น แต่ว่าในเรื่องผลกำไรน่าจะเป็นเรื่องการลดการขาดทุนมากกว่า เพราะว่าบริษัทของ PMS ยังมีปัญหาขาดทุนแต่ก็จะลดลง</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>What are the revenues from Phononic?</p>
                <p>I can't disclose absolute revenue, but the business will be meaningful — potentially a top-five or top-seven customer by next year, and more if additional projects come in.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>คำถามเกี่ยวกับรายได้จาก Phononic ว่าจะเป็นกี่เปอร์เซ็นต์ ขอแจ้งว่าไม่สามารถที่จะเปิดเผยข้อมูลได้ในรายละเอียด แต่ว่าลูกค้าของเรา Phononic จะมีความยินดีที่จะให้เปิดเผยข้อมูลในลักษณะที่ว่าเรามีธุรกิจกับเขาเป็นธุรกิจอะไรซึ่งคาดว่าถ้าเริ่มผลิตแล้ว แล้วเป็นไปได้ดี ลูกค้า Phononics จะเป็นลูกค้าระดับต้นๆ ของ Hana</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>FT1 status?</p>
                <p>PTT is the major shareholder and I must be guided by their announcements. There's no change — the project is currently on hold.</p>
                <p class="th" lang="th"><span class="thtag">TH</span>คำถามเกี่ยวกับการร่วมทุนกับ ปตท. อย่างที่คุณริชาร์ดเคยแจ้งไว้ว่าเราเป็นผู้ถือหุ้น ผู้ลงทุน ถ้าเทียบกับ ปตท. เราเป็นรายเล็กกว่า เราก็จะไม่สามารถตอบคำถามได้แทน ปตท. แต่ว่าตอนนี้โปรเจกต์กำลัง hold ไว้ก่อน</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>Risk of delays on Phononic?</p>
                <p>The main risk is qualification and testing, which we don't expect to be a problem. Worst case, a delay in qualification delays the ramp-up — it doesn't stop the business. The mass-production line remains on schedule.</p>

                <p class="tq"><span class="qmark">Q</span>Any other AI activities beyond the three presented?</p>
                <p>We do have others, but they are not yet large enough to be meaningful, so we don't discuss them. We only talk about AI businesses that will be meaningful for Hana; if the others grow, we'll open them up.</p>
              </div>

